>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'PL-9643 is Palatin’s investigational melanocortin-agonist eye drop for dry eye disease — potentially a first-in-class treatment.',
      'It works on the melanocortin system’s anti-inflammatory, resolution-promoting biology, calming the ocular-surface inflammation that drives dry eye rather than just lubricating the eye.',
      'In the pivotal Phase 3 MELODY-1 trial (575 patients), it met its co-primary symptom endpoint of ocular pain plus several secondary symptom endpoints.',
      'Symptom improvement appeared by week 2 and kept building through 12 weeks, with fewer treatment-related adverse events than the vehicle control.',
      'Two further Phase 3 trials, MELODY-2 and MELODY-3, are evaluating both the signs and the symptoms of dry eye.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    PL-9643 takes the melanocortin system somewhere unexpected: the eye. It is one of
    Palatin Technologies' investigational melanocortin agonists — this one an eye drop for
    <strong>dry eye disease</strong>, and like <a href="/pl-8177">PL-8177</a> in the gut,
    it is built on the system's anti-inflammatory arm rather than its pigment or appetite
    roles.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>Calming the surface, not just wetting it</h2>
  <p>
    Dry eye disease is not only a lubrication problem; a large part of it is
    <strong>inflammation</strong> of the ocular surface that becomes self-sustaining.
    PL-9643 activates melanocortin receptors on the eye to dampen that inflammation and
    push it toward resolution — the same broad biology that makes
    <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a> a natural anti-inflammatory signal, applied topically.<Cite n={1} />
    That mechanism is different both from artificial tears, which lubricate, and from
    broad immunosuppressants, which blunt immunity generally.
  </p>

  <h2>The Phase 3 result</h2>
  <p>
    PL-9643's pivotal trial, <strong>MELODY-1</strong>, enrolled 575 patients with
    moderate-to-severe dry eye. It met its co-primary <em>symptom</em> endpoint of ocular
    pain (P&lt;0.025) along with several secondary symptom endpoints, with symptom relief
    emerging by week 2 and continuing to build through 12 weeks — and it did so with
    <em>fewer</em> treatment-related adverse events than the vehicle control.<Cite n={1} /><Cite n={2} />
    Independent coverage framed it as a promising, potentially first-in-class approach.<Cite n={3} />
    The program is not finished: two further trials, <strong>MELODY-2</strong> and
    <strong>MELODY-3</strong>, are designed to evaluate both the signs and the symptoms of
    the disease — the fuller bar a dry-eye drug must clear.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    PL-9643 is investigational, and a single positive symptom trial is a milestone, not an
    approval — the remaining MELODY studies still have to deliver. But it is a striking
    demonstration of the melanocortin system's reach: the same anti-inflammatory signalling
    behind pigment biology and gut disease, formulated as an eye drop. For the underlying
    biology, see <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a>; for the wider landscape, see the
    <a href="/pipeline">melanocortin pipeline</a>.
  </p>

